    "body": "# POS delivery, without the app\n\n> We added a delivery-order feature to our own POS. A voucher with a QR code goes in every bag, the code opens our own order page, and the next-day order lands in the same admin + kitchen flow we already run. Then we deliver it ourselves.\n\n## Hooks — write 5+, pick 1\n1. I added delivery to my POS. So customers can order from us without the delivery app.\n2. Every bag that leaves my kitchen has a QR code inside. It's how we skip the delivery app.\n3. The delivery app takes a cut and keeps the customer. So I built the feature myself.\n4. We delivered our first order this week. No app involved. My POS did the whole thing.\n5. My customers order delivery from a voucher in their bag. I built that into our POS.\n\n**Chosen hook:** #1\n\n## Beat sheet\n\n| Beat | Time | Voiceover | On-screen / B-roll |\n|------|------|-----------|--------------------|\n| Hook | 0–3s | I added delivery to my POS. So customers can order from us without the delivery app. | Screen-record: our order page open on a phone |\n| Context | 3–8s | The app takes a cut of every order, and the customer stays theirs. I don't even get their number. | Proof shot #1: commission line circled on the merchant statement (NOT spoken) |\n| Body A | 8–15s | Now every bag that leaves the kitchen has a voucher inside. On it, a QR code. It opens our order page. | Hands packing a bag, voucher goes in, close-up of the QR |\n| Re-hook | 15–17s | But the QR code isn't the clever part. | Face snap, ~2s |\n| Body B | 17–28s | Next day they scan it and order the same food, straight from us. And that order lands in the same system. Admin sees it, the kitchen gets the ticket. | Phone scans QR → order page → tap order. Cut to admin screen ping |\n| Re-hook 2 | 28–32s | No new app, nothing for the staff to learn. | Face return, slower |\n| Payoff | 32–40s | It's just another ticket on the rail, and one of our guys rides it over. | Proof shot #2: order popping onto the kitchen screen, then the bike out the door |\n| Close | 40–45s | First one came in this week. Two bowls, same street as the shop. | Bag handed over at the doorstep |\n\n## Voiceover — clean read\n\nI added delivery to my POS. So customers can order from us without the delivery app. The app takes a cut of every order, and the customer stays theirs. I don't even get their number. Now every bag that leaves the kitchen has a voucher inside. On it, a QR code. It opens our order page. But the QR code isn't the clever part. Next day they scan it and order the same food, straight from us. And that order lands in the same system. Admin sees it, the kitchen gets the ticket. No new app, nothing for the staff to learn. It's just another ticket on the rail, and one of our guys rides it over. First one came in this week. Two bowls, same street as the shop.\n\n## On-screen text\n- **Pinned (top):** Delivery. Without the app.\n- **Key captions / numbers (these carry the rupiah — never spoken):** the app's commission line circled on a real merchant statement. Caption chunks: \"voucher in every bag\" / \"scan → our order page\" / \"straight to the kitchen.\"\n\n## B-roll shot list\n- [ ] Hands packing a bag, dropping the voucher in, close-up of the QR\n- [ ] Screen-record: phone scans the QR → order page → tap order\n- [ ] Admin screen receiving the order (real notification ping)\n- [ ] Kitchen printer spitting the ticket, ticket going up on the rail\n- [ ] Code editor / the POS feature commit (the \"I built this\" shot)\n- [ ] Our guy heading out with the bag, doorstep handoff\n\n## Proof shot\n- **Number on screen:** #1 the delivery app's commission line circled (never spoken). #2 the order landing live on the kitchen screen.\n- **Lands on this line:** #1 on \"takes a cut of every order.\" #2 on \"the kitchen gets the ticket.\"\n\n## Post caption + hashtags\n\nNew feature in our POS. Every bag gets a voucher with a QR code, the code opens our own order page, and tomorrow's order lands straight on the kitchen screen. We deliver it ourselves. First one came in this week, same street as the shop.\n\n#buildinpublic #pos #restauranttech #smallbusiness #softwaredevelopment\n\n## Notes\n- **Pronunciation flags:** \"voucher\" (VOW-cher), rehearse once. \"QR code\" is clean. Keep \"scan it and order\" unhurried.\n- **Music / SFX:** light. Real notification ping when the order lands on the admin screen, printer sound for the kitchen ticket.\n- **Facts to confirm before shoot:** which shop this is live at, and the real first direct order (\"two bowls, same street\" is a placeholder — swap in what actually happened). Blur customer name/address on the admin screen."
