    "body": "# AI agent reads my restaurant's data (ep. 2)\n\n> Episode 2 of the data-app story. Ep 1 pooled all my restaurant's numbers into one app. This time I put an AI on top of that data and let it read. In two months it caught a dish that quietly stopped making money, shifts I'm overstaffed on, and which days actually spike — things I run the place and never noticed.\n\n## Hooks — write 5+, pick 1\n1. I connected an AI to my restaurant's data two months ago. It keeps catching things I never would've.\n2. I gave an AI two months of my restaurant's numbers. It found money I was losing and never saw.\n3. A dish I sell every day was barely making money. I didn't catch it. The AI did.\n4. I built the app. Then I let an AI read it. Now it tells me what's wrong before I notice.\n5. I don't check my dashboard anymore. I just ask the AI what's bleeding.\n\n**Chosen hook:** #1 (leaning) — #3 is the more specific alt if testing\n\n## Beat sheet\n\n| Beat | Time | Voiceover | On-screen / B-roll |\n|------|------|-----------|--------------------|\n| Hook | 0–5s | I connected an AI to my restaurant's data two months ago. And it keeps telling me things I run the place and never noticed. | Face, tight. Pinned \"AI reading my restaurant\" |\n| Context (callback) | 5–14s | Last video, I built one app that pulls all my numbers into one place. Sales, labor, expenses, all of it. So this time I just gave the whole thing to the AI and let it read. | Quick callback clip of the ep-1 dashboard, then the AI chat opening |\n| Body A (hero catch) | 14–38s | First week, it flagged a dish. One we sell every single day. The ingredient price had been creeping up for months, and that plate was barely making money anymore. I never saw it, because the total still looked fine. It saw it, because it reads every line. | **Proof shot 1:** AI message flagging the dish; line chart of the ingredient price creeping up (number circled, on screen only) |\n| Re-hook | 38–44s | And that dish wasn't the only thing. | Face snap |\n| Body B (quick trio) | 44–66s | It told me which shifts have too many people on. The slow afternoons where I'm paying more staff than the sales need. It found which days actually spike, and why. Turns out it's payday week, every time. Stuff I could've worked out myself, if I ever had the hours to sit and look. I don't. It does. | B-roll: quiet shift floor; AI answer on screen; **Proof shot 2:** payday-week spike on the calendar/chart |\n| Re-hook 2 (reframe) | 66–72s | So now I don't dig through the dashboard. | Face return |\n| Payoff | 72–84s | I just ask it how last week went, or what's getting more expensive, or where I'm losing money. And it answers, because it's been reading the whole time. | Screen-record: typing a question, the AI answering |\n| Close | 84–90s | It caught that dish on a Tuesday. I changed the recipe Wednesday. | The dish being remade / a hand adjusting the portion |\n\n## Voiceover — clean read\n<!-- The full spoken track, exactly the way it's said. Read it aloud once. -->\n\nI connected an AI to my restaurant's data two months ago. And it keeps telling me things I run the place and never noticed. Last video, I built one app that pulls all my numbers into one place. Sales, labor, expenses, all of it. So this time I just gave the whole thing to the AI and let it read. First week, it flagged a dish. One we sell every single day. The ingredient price had been creeping up for months, and that plate was barely making money anymore. I never saw it, because the total still looked fine. It saw it, because it reads every line. And that dish wasn't the only thing. It told me which shifts have too many people on. The slow afternoons where I'm paying more staff than the sales need. It found which days actually spike, and why. Turns out it's payday week, every time. Stuff I could've worked out myself, if I ever had the hours to sit and look. I don't. It does. So now I don't dig through the dashboard. I just ask it how last week went, or what's getting more expensive, or where I'm losing money. And it answers, because it's been reading the whole time. It caught that dish on a Tuesday. I changed the recipe Wednesday.\n\n## On-screen text\n- **Pinned (top):** I gave my restaurant data to an AI (hold 5–10s, restate the hook)\n- **Key captions / numbers (these carry the rupiah — never spoken):** the dish's shrinking margin, the ingredient price line going up, the slow-shift labor vs sales, the payday-week spike — all shown and circled, never spoken. Highlight \"two months,\" \"payday week,\" \"every line.\"\n\n## B-roll shot list\n- [ ] Callback clip of the ep-1 dashboard (1–2s), then the AI chat opening\n- [ ] AI message flagging the dish (the catch) — proof shot 1\n- [ ] Line chart of the ingredient price creeping up over the two months (number circled)\n- [ ] The dish in question, plated, on the line (name the real one)\n- [ ] Quiet/slow shift on the floor (the overstaffed afternoon)\n- [ ] Calendar or chart showing the payday-week spike — proof shot 2\n- [ ] Screen-record: typing a question, the AI answering\n- [ ] The dish being remade / hand adjusting the portion (close)\n\n## Proof shot\n- **Number on screen:** (1) the AI's flag on the dish + the ingredient price line trending up; (2) the payday-week sales spike. Money kept on screen only, framed as cost / what's leaking — never spoken. Max two.\n- **Lands on this line:** Proof 1 on \"that plate was barely making money anymore.\" Proof 2 on \"it's payday week, every time.\"\n\n## Post caption + hashtags\n\nEpisode 2. First I built one app that pooled all my restaurant's data. Then I put an AI on top of it and let it read for two months. It caught a dish that quietly stopped making money, the shifts I'm overstaffed on, and which days actually spike. Things I run the place and never noticed. Now I don't dig through the dashboard, I just ask it.\n\n#buildinpublic #aiagents #automation #smallbusiness #systems\n\n## Notes\n- **Episode 2** — follows `scripts/systems/bookkeeping-12-hours-to-30-minutes.md` (the data app). Open on the callback clip so ep-1 viewers get the payoff.\n- **SWAP IN THE REAL SPECIFIC:** name the actual dish and the actual ingredient that crept up (e.g. ayam geprek + the chicken or oil price). Generic \"a dish\" is a placeholder — the real name is what makes the catch land. Same for the spike cause: confirm it's really payday week (or swap to rain / a delivery promo).\n- **Pronunciation flags:** \"ingredient\" (in-GRE-dient). \"dashboard\" clean. \"recipe\" (RE-ci-pe). Keep \"staff\" crisp.\n- **Music / SFX:** light. Soft notification \"ping\" SFX on the AI flagging the dish. No music under the close."
