    "body": "# Bookkeeping: 12 hours a month to 30 minutes\n\n> My restaurant's books took 12–16 hours a month because every number lived in a different place — attendance in a book, bonuses on a page, expenses and receipts in a pile, sales in the POS. I built one app everything feeds into, so closing the month is now one dashboard, one button, about 30 minutes.\n\n## Hooks — write 5+, pick 1\n1. My restaurant's bookkeeping used to take twelve hours a month. Now it's thirty minutes. Same restaurant.\n2. I wasn't bad at bookkeeping. My numbers just lived in five different places.\n3. Every month I lost two work days to bookkeeping. So I built my way out.\n4. Attendance in one book. Receipts in a pile. Sales in the POS. That's why my books took twelve hours.\n5. I built a POS for my own restaurant. The point wasn't sales. It was getting twelve hours back.\n\n**Chosen hook:** #1 (leaning)\n\n## Beat sheet\n\n| Beat | Time | Voiceover | On-screen / B-roll |\n|------|------|-----------|--------------------|\n| Hook | 0–5s | My restaurant's bookkeeping used to take twelve hours a month. Some months sixteen. Now it's about thirty minutes. Same restaurant, same numbers. | Face, tight. Pinned text \"12 hrs → 30 min\" |\n| Context | 5–14s | And I wasn't slow at it. The problem was where everything lived. | Cut to desk: book, receipt pile, POS — scattered |\n| Body A | 14–32s | Attendance was in one book. Bonuses, I wrote those on a different page. Expenses and receipts were a pile on my desk. And the sales sat in the POS, separate from all of it. | Each source named as it's said: attendance book, bonus page, receipt pile, POS screen |\n| Re-hook | 32–40s | So closing the month meant collecting the same numbers from five places, by hand, every time. The math was never the hard part. The gathering was. | Face snap, slower. Highlight \"five places\" |\n| Body B | 40–58s | So I built one app, and I made every part of the restaurant feed into it. The staff clock in there. Bonuses, expenses, a photo of a receipt, the sales. It all lands in the same place now. | Screen-record: app, staff clocking in, receipt photo upload |\n| Re-hook 2 | 58–66s | So the month isn't a job anymore. It's a screen. | Face return |\n| Payoff | 66–82s | One dashboard, one button, and the whole month is just there. Labor, what we spent, what came in. Thirty minutes, and most of that is me just checking it looks right. | Proof shot: dashboard populating on one tap |\n| Close | 82–90s | Last month I closed the books waiting for my coffee. Didn't even open my laptop. | Phone in hand at a café, coffee arriving |\n\n## Voiceover — clean read\n<!-- The full spoken track, exactly the way it's said. Read it aloud once. -->\n\nMy restaurant's bookkeeping used to take twelve hours a month. Some months sixteen. Now it's about thirty minutes. Same restaurant, same numbers. And I wasn't slow at it. The problem was where everything lived. Attendance was in one book. Bonuses, I wrote those on a different page. Expenses and receipts were a pile on my desk. And the sales sat in the POS, separate from all of it. So closing the month meant collecting the same numbers from five places, by hand, every time. The math was never the hard part. The gathering was. So I built one app, and I made every part of the restaurant feed into it. The staff clock in there. Bonuses, expenses, a photo of a receipt, the sales. It all lands in the same place now. So the month isn't a job anymore. It's a screen. One dashboard, one button, and the whole month is just there. Labor, what we spent, what came in. Thirty minutes, and most of that is me just checking it looks right. Last month I closed the books waiting for my coffee. Didn't even open my laptop.\n\n## On-screen text\n- **Pinned (top):** 12 hours → 30 minutes (hold 5–10s)\n- **Key captions / numbers (these carry the rupiah — never spoken):** count-up on the time delta \"12 hrs → 30 min\" on first reveal. Highlight \"five places,\" \"one button.\" Any money on the dashboard (labor / spent / came in) stays on screen only, framed as cost, never spoken.\n\n## B-roll shot list\n- [ ] Desk with everything scattered: attendance book, bonus page, receipt pile, POS screen in one frame\n- [ ] Each source in sequence as it's named (book → page → receipts → POS)\n- [ ] The app open: staff clocking in\n- [ ] Photographing a receipt straight into the app\n- [ ] Dashboard populating on one tap (the proof shot)\n- [ ] Closing the books on the phone at a café, coffee arriving\n\n## Proof shot\n- **Number on screen:** the time delta \"12 hrs → 30 min\"; the month dashboard (labor / spent / came in) with any money kept on-screen only and framed as cost\n- **Lands on this line:** \"One dashboard, one button, and the whole month is just there.\"\n\n## Post caption + hashtags\n\nMy restaurant's books used to take twelve hours a month, because every number lived somewhere different. Attendance in a book, bonuses on a page, receipts in a pile, sales in the POS. I built one app everything feeds into. Now closing the month is one dashboard, about thirty minutes.\n\n#buildinpublic #automation #smallbusiness #systems #restaurant\n\n## Notes\n- **Pronunciation flags:** \"bookkeeping\" (book-keeping, crisp). \"attendance\" (a-TEN-dance). \"receipt\" (re-SEET, silent p). \"dashboard\" clean.\n- **Music / SFX:** light. Soft click SFX on the one-button dashboard reveal. Count-up SFX on the \"12 hrs → 30 min\" pinned text."
