    "body": "# From design agency to software\n\n> I ran a design/branding agency for years. The reason I switched to building software was watching pretty brands sit on top of broken operations.\n\n## Hooks — write 5+, pick 1\n1. I used to make logos. Now I build the system behind the counter.\n2. I ran a design agency for years. Then I stopped on purpose.\n3. The prettiest brand I ever made was for a business that was quietly falling apart.\n4. Branding was the easy part. Nobody was fixing the actual problem.\n5. I spent years making things look good. Then I got bored of the surface.\n\n**Chosen hook:** #1\n\n## Beat sheet\n\n| Beat | Time | Voiceover | On-screen / B-roll |\n|------|------|-----------|--------------------|\n| Hook | 0–3s | I used to make logos. Now I build the system behind the counter. | Throwback: old brand work on screen |\n| Context | 3–8s | I ran a design agency for years. Websites, branding, the whole thing. | Old portfolio scroll |\n| Body A | 8–15s | And I was good at it. But I kept noticing the same thing. A business would pay for a beautiful brand, and behind it, the operations were held together with a group chat and one tired manager. | Split: polished brand vs messy backend |\n| Re-hook | 15–17s | The logo wasn't the problem. | Face snap |\n| Body B | 17–28s | So I started asking what actually slowed them down. It was never the design. It was the booking, the stock, the orders nobody could track. | Whiteboard sketch of a workflow |\n| Re-hook 2 | 28–32s | That's the part I actually wanted to fix. | Face return |\n| Payoff | 32–40s | So I learned to build the thing under the brand, not just the brand. Now I sit with an operator, find the one bottleneck, and build for that. | Cursor / code editor + a live system |\n| Close | 40–45s | Three months in. Still figuring it out. | Working at the desk, late |\n\n## Voiceover — clean read\n\nI used to make logos. Now I build the system behind the counter. I ran a design agency for years. Websites, branding, the whole thing. And I was good at it. But I kept noticing the same thing. A business would pay for a beautiful brand, and behind it, the operations were held together with a group chat and one tired manager. The logo wasn't the problem. So I started asking what actually slowed them down. It was never the design. It was the booking, the stock, the orders nobody could track. That's the part I actually wanted to fix. So I learned to build the thing under the brand, not just the brand. Now I sit with an operator, find the one bottleneck, and build for that. Three months in. Still figuring it out.\n\n## On-screen text\n- **Pinned (top):** From logos to systems.\n- **Key captions / numbers:** \"3 months in\" chip at the close. (No revenue shown — this one's a story.)\n\n## B-roll shot list\n- [ ] Old brand/portfolio work on screen (throwback, date stamp)\n- [ ] Split screen: polished brand vs messy backend\n- [ ] Whiteboard sketch of a workflow, drawn live\n- [ ] Cursor / code editor with a real system\n- [ ] Desk, late, working\n\n## Proof shot\n- **Number on screen:** none required (story video) — optional \"3 months in\" timestamp\n- **Lands on this line:** \"Three months in. Still figuring it out.\"\n\n## Post caption + hashtags\n\nRan a design agency for years. Switched to building software because the brand was never the bottleneck — the operations were. Three months into this. Still figuring it out.\n\n#buildinpublic #designtodev #founderstory #automation #operator\n\n## Notes\n- **Pronunciation flags:** \"operations\" (4 syllables — say \"ops\" where natural). \"bottleneck\" crisp.\n- **Music / SFX:** warm, low. No drop. Let the throwback breathe."
